2025_10_pnnl_s5_EDA

This follows Tyler Sagendorf’s Section 5 Exploratory Data Analysis Tutorial from Proteomics Data Analysis in R/Bioconductor (pnnl)

  • oca.set details - https://rdrr.io/github/vladpetyuk/vp.misc/man/oca.set.html

    • Processed iTRAQ data from both PNNL & JHU sites (from CPTAC study)

      • an MSnID instance - 8103 proteins by 73 features

    • CPTAC det https://statomics.github.io/PDA/pda_tutorialPreprocessing.html

5.1 Count Features in Samples

https://pnnl-comp-mass-spec.github.io/proteomics-data-analysis-tutorial/count-features-in-samples.html

# Count no. of features ID per sample - using colSums that are not NA in exprs(oca.set)

# Calculate the no. of proteins ID (not NA) in each sample
oca.set$num_proteins <- colSums(!is.na(exprs(oca.set)))
# vector of no. proteins stored in pData(oca.set)
# pData(oca.set) should be in final col
# summary (5 nums)
summary(oca.set$num_proteins)
##    Min. 1st Qu.  Median    Mean 3rd Qu.    Max. 
##    6594    6957    7286    7225    7463    7798
# as horizontal box plot
boxplot(oca.set$num_proteins, horizontal = TRUE,
        xlab = "No. of Proteins Detected")

# a scatter plot with more info
plot(oca.set$num_proteins, 
     pch = 19, # solid circle shape
     xlab = "Sample Index",
     ylab = "Number of Proteins Detected") 

# chaotic but useful for showing any major outliers
# shows distribution - density ploy has the benefits of both box & scatter plots
# Kernel density plot 
plot(density(oca.set$num_proteins, na.rm = TRUE),
     xlim = range(oca.set$num_proteins, na.rm = TRUE),
     main = "Density Plot", xlab = "No. of Proteins Detected")

# shows peaks ~6900-7000 & 7300-7500

5.3 Estimate Blood Contamination

  • https://pnnl-comp-mass-spec.github.io/proteomics-data-analysis-tutorial/estimate-blood-contamination.html

  • Search for major blood proteins with grepl function & summarise their abundance within each sample to get reasonable estimates.

  • Udinh

  • hemoglobin

    • subunit alpha 1: NP_000549.1 | subunit alpha 2: NP_000508.1 | subunit beta: NP_000509.1 | subunit gamma-1: NP_000550.2 | subunit gamma-2: NP_000175.1

  • albumin:

    • NP_000468.1

  • fibrinogen

    • alpha chain isoform alpha precursor: NP_068657.1

    • alpha chain isoform alpha-E preprotein: NP_000499.1

  • spectrin

    • alpha chain, erythrocytic 1: NP_003117.2

    • beta chain, erythrocytic 1: NP_001342365.1

# Create vector containing blod proteins
# Blood protein IDs
blood_prot <- c("NP_000549.1", "NP_000508.1", "NP_000509.1", "NP_000550.2",
                "NP_000175.1", # 5 hemoglobin protein subunits
                "NP_000468.1", # 1 albumin
                "NP_068657.1", "NP_000499.1", # 2 fibrnogen
                "NP_003117.2", "NP_001342365.1") # 2 Spectrin

# Select entries that match one of the blood proteins
idx <- featureNames(oca.set) %in% blood_prot # indexing match
blood_contam <- colMeans(exprs(oca.set)[idx, ], na.rm = TRUE) # sample means
# GOOD INDEXING EXAMPLE
# Kernel density plot
plot(density(blood_contam, na.rm = TRUE), 
     xlim = range(blood_contam, na.rm = TRUE),
     main = "Blood Contamination", xlab = "Average Protein Abundance")
